  "prompt": "What does a presidential censure look like?",
  "response": "A presidential censure is a formal statement of disapproval or condemnation issued by Congress against a sitting or former president. Here's what it typically involves:\n\n1. Legislative Process:\n- Usually initiated in the House or Senate\n- Requires a majority vote to pass\n- Primarily a symbolic reprimand\n- Does not remove the president from office\n\n2. Content:\n- Detailed explanation of specific actions being condemned\n- Formal language describing the president's alleged misconduct\n- Clear statement of disapproval\n\n3. Historical Precedent:\n- Rare occurrence in U.S. history\n- Most recently discussed during presidencies like Trump and Clinton\n- Serves as a public rebuke and historical record\n\n4. Consequences:\n- No legal punishment\n- Primarily a political and moral statement\n- Can damage presidential reputation\n- Potentially impacts political standing\n\n5. Format:\n- Typically a written resolution\n- Read into the Congressional record\n- Officially documented in congressional proceedings\n\nWhile censure is a serious political action, it is essentially a strong public criticism without direct legal ramifications like impeachment or removal from office.",
